# Refactoring Standards

## Purpose
Refactor safely without changing behavior unexpectedly.

## Rules
- Establish a baseline before refactoring.
- Prefer small refactors with tests passing between steps.
- Do not mix refactoring with new behavior unless explicitly planned.
- Keep public interfaces stable unless the task is to change them.
- Replace duplicated logic only when duplication is real and meaningful.
- Avoid abstractions that hide simple code.
- Do not move experimental notebook code into reusable modules until there is a real reuse case.

## Refactoring Flow
1. Identify current behavior.
2. Run related tests or define a manual baseline.
3. Make one structural change.
4. Run related tests or repeat the manual check.
5. Repeat only after the system is green again.

## Checklist
- [ ] Baseline behavior is known.
- [ ] Refactor does not add new features.
- [ ] Tests or manual checks verify unchanged behavior.
- [ ] Naming and module boundaries are clearer after the change.
- [ ] Documentation is updated if architecture changed.

